Data Cleaning and Feature Generation

Convert Variable Types
# convert variables to appropriate type
data.train$Survived <- as.logical(data.train$Survived)
data.train$Pclass <- as.factor(data.train$Pclass)
data.train$Name <- as.character(data.train$Name)
data.train$Ticket <- as.character(data.train$Ticket)
data.train$Cabin <- as.character(data.train$Cabin)

data.test$Pclass <- as.factor(data.test$Pclass)
data.test$Name <- as.character(data.test$Name)
data.test$Ticket <- as.character(data.test$Ticket)
data.test$Cabin <- as.character(data.test$Cabin)
Transformations
# transform the fare variable, since it's right-skewed
data.train$Fare <- ifelse(data.train$Fare >= 1, log(data.train$Fare), 0)
data.test$Fare <- ifelse(data.test$Fare >= 1, log(data.test$Fare), 0)
data.test$Fare <- ifelse(is.na(data.test$Fare), 0, data.test$Fare)
Feature Generation
# generate dummy variables to capture the signal inherent in the passengers' names; then, delete the name variable [train]
data.train$isMr <- grepl("Mr\\.", data.train$Name)
data.train$isMrs <- grepl("Mrs\\.", data.train$Name)
data.train$isMaster <- grepl("Master\\.", data.train$Name)
data.train$isMiss <- grepl("Miss\\.", data.train$Name)

data.train$hasParenth <- grepl("\\(", data.train$Name)
data.train$hasQuote <- grepl("\"", data.train$Name)

data.train$Name <- NULL
# generate dummy variables to capture the signal inherent in the passengers' names; then, delete the name variable [test]
data.test$isMr <- grepl("Mr\\.", data.test$Name)
data.test$isMrs <- grepl("Mrs\\.", data.test$Name)
data.test$isMaster <- grepl("Master\\.", data.test$Name)
data.test$isMiss <- grepl("Miss\\.", data.test$Name)

data.test$hasParenth <- grepl("\\(", data.test$Name)
data.test$hasQuote <- grepl("\"", data.test$Name)

data.test$Name <- NULL
# generate dummy variables from ticket and cabin variables, then delete original variables [train]

# dealing with ticket number
data.train$fiveCharTicket <- nchar(data.train$Ticket) == 5
data.train$sixCharTicket <- nchar(data.train$Ticket) == 6
data.train$numericTicket <- !grepl("[A-Za-z]", data.train$Ticket)
data.train$ticketLength <- nchar(data.train$Ticket)
data.train$Ticket <- NULL

# dealing with cabin number
data.train$hasCabin <- grepl("[A-Z]", data.train$Cabin)
data.train$multiCabin <- grepl(" [A-Z]", data.train$Cabin)
data.train$Cabin <- NULL
# generate dummy variables from ticket and cabin variables, then delete original variables [test]

# dealing with ticket number
data.test$fiveCharTicket <- nchar(data.test$Ticket) == 5
data.test$sixCharTicket <- nchar(data.test$Ticket) == 6
data.test$numericTicket <- !grepl("[A-Za-z]", data.test$Ticket)
data.test$ticketLength <- nchar(data.test$Ticket)
data.test$Ticket <- NULL

# dealing with cabin number
data.test$hasCabin <- grepl("[A-Z]", data.test$Cabin)

data.test$Cabin <- NULL
# new feature for those who didn't pay to ride
data.train$freeRide <- data.train$Fare == 0
data.test$freeRide <- data.test$Fare == 0
# feature for if the passenger had no family with them
data.train$isAlone <- (data.train$SibSp + data.train$Parch) == 0
data.test$isAlone <- (data.test$SibSp + data.test$Parch) == 0
Imputing Missing Values
# some missing ports of embarkation in the training data
data.train %>% filter(!Embarked %in% c("C", "Q", "S"))
##   PassengerId Survived Pclass    Sex Age SibSp Parch     Fare Embarked  isMr
## 1          62     TRUE      1 female  38     0     0 4.382027          FALSE

## 1          TRUE            6     TRUE      FALSE    FALSE    TRUE
## 2          TRUE            6     TRUE      FALSE    FALSE    TRUE
# only two records, so not a big deal, but let's just impute using the most common port
data.train$Embarked[data.train$Embarked == ""] <- names(which.max(table(data.train$Embarked)))[1]
data.train$Embarked <- droplevels(data.train$Embarked)
# not a problem on the test set
data.test %>% filter(!Embarked %in% c("C", "Q", "S"))
##  [1] PassengerId    Pclass         Sex            Age            SibSp
##  [6] Parch          Fare           Embarked       isMr           isMrs

## [21] freeRide       isAlone
## <0 rows> (or 0-length row.names)
# one NA to fix in the fare variable of the test set; just impute using the median (right-skewed), since it's only one point
#data.test[!complete.cases(data.test),]
#data.test$Fare[!complete.cases(data.test)] <- median(data.test$Fare, na.rm = TRUE)
# missing ages: 177/891 records = nearly 20% of the data... this is problematic, for sure. need to impute values.
#data.train %>% filter(is.na(data.train$Age)) 
# knn-imputation on age and center/scale all numeric vars
preProcValues <- preProcess(data.train,
                            method = c("knnImpute"),
                            k = 20,
                            knnSummary = mean)

data.train$imputedAge <- predict(preProcValues, data.train)$Age

# create a weights variable to limit the extent to which observations whose age variable was originally missing and subsequently imputed
w <- 0.9 # for easy reference in other code chunks
data.train$ageWeight<- rep(1, nrow(data.train))
data.train$ageWeight[is.na(data.train$Age)] <- w

# create a new iteration of the training data for backtracking, if need be
data.train2 <- data.train %>% select(-Age)
# knn-imputation on age for the test set; same process as the one above for the train set
# there is no data leakage here because we're just using the information about the other
# passenger in the set (known beforehand) to approximate age
preProcValues <- preProcess(data.test,
                            method = c("knnImpute"),
                            k = 20,
                            knnSummary = mean)

data.test$imputedAge <- predict(preProcValues, data.test)$Age

rm(preProcValues)

data.test$ageWeight<- rep(1, nrow(data.test))
data.test$ageWeight[is.na(data.test$Age)] <- w

data.test2 <- data.test %>% select(-Age)
Scale Numeric Variables
# scale numeric variables

data.test2$SibSp <- scale(data.test2$SibSp)

It looks like most of the logical predictors will be useful as features. We probably won’t use sixCharTicket and numericTicket to avoid overfitting.

# split bar charts for the each of the factors

d <- data.train2 %>% select_if(is.factor)

Each of these appears to have some good signal in it. we’ll use them all in our models.

# see if there's anything that can be salvaged from the age variable
ggplot(original.train, aes(Age)) + geom_density(aes(fill = as.factor(Survived), alpha = 0.5)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 10, color = "purple") + geom_vline(xintercept = 30, color = "purple")
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

nrow(original.train %>% filter(Age < 10)) / nrow(original.train)
## [1] 0.06958474

Though there appears to be some signal (difference between probability density over different target values) for age < 10, this only comprises about 7% of the observations. With that said, we’ll just omit the data variable from our models. For that reason, we’ll also forgo the use of the ageWeight variable in our models as a counterbalance for imputation.

UPDATE: What if we compress that signal for ages 0-10, 10-30, and 30+ into two (omit the third level to avoid multicollinearity – specifically, rank deficiency due to perfect multicollinearity) binary variable, rather than discarding age altogether?

# the age distribution is actually much different for those who survived and those who didn't, given the passenger's age was below average (scaled age = 0)
ggplot(data.train2 %>% filter(imputedAge < 0), aes(imputedAge, fill = Survived)) +
  geom_density(aes(alpha = 0.5)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = -0.9, color = "purple") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = -1.5, color = "purple")

# let's construct two binary variables to capture this signal

data.train2$isYouth <- ifelse(data.train2$imputedAge < -0.9, TRUE, FALSE)
data.train2$isYoungAdult <- ifelse(data.train2$imputedAge > -0.9 & data.train2$imputedAge < 0, TRUE, FALSE)

data.test2$isYouth <- ifelse(data.test2$imputedAge < -0.9, TRUE, FALSE)
data.test2$isYoungAdult <- ifelse(data.test2$imputedAge > -0.9 & data.test2$imputedAge < 0, TRUE, FALSE)

The unpruned tree correctly classifies around 87% of the training data, but it’s too complex, so it’ll likely overfit the data and perform poorly on the test set.

After pruning the tree by manually increasing the complexity parameter, we get a much more easilly interpretable model, and still maintain decent performance (~83%) on the training data. With that said, an individual tree will almost assuredly struggle to generalize to observations beyond its training set, so it’s a good idea to train a few tree-based ensemble models (e.g., random forest, boosted trees) to address potential overfitting.

# generate predictions for the test set
fitTree.predictions <- predict(fitTree, newdata = data.test3, type = "class")
mean(as.logical(fitTree.predictions))
## [1] 0.3875598

GLM + Tree Ensemble

# since the GLM and tree have completely different model structures, one might expect that they'd each identify unique characteristics of the signal; hence, it might be useful to create an ensemble of both models

fitSimpleEnsemble.predictions <- ((predict(fitGLM, type = "response") + predict(fitTree, type = "prob")[,2]) / 2) > 0.5

Generate Model Matrices for Use in More Complex Models

# model matrices of the data; used with glmnet and xgboost
X <- model.matrix(Survived ~ . , data.train3)
X.test <- model.matrix(~ . , data.test3)

LASSO (L1) Regression

# regularization: elastic net with alpha = 1 -> LASSO (L1) regression
# by penalizing high coefficient values, we can limit overfitting of the original GLM
elastic.cv <- cv.glmnet(X, data.train3$Survived, family = "binomial", type.measure = "class", alpha = 1)
fitElastic <- glmnet(X, data.train3$Survived, family = "binomial", type.measure = "class", alpha = 1,
                     lambda = min(elastic.cv$lambda))
confusionMatrix(as.factor(predict(fitElastic, newx = X, type = "class")), as.factor(data.train3$Survived), positive = "TRUE")

Random Forest

# random forest; takes a bit longer to train (~ 5-10 mins)

# theoretically reasonable mtry value = sqrt(p), which is about 4 in this case; we'll tune from 1-10, using
# repeated cross-validation and up-/down-sampling to counteract the imbalance in the target values

rfGrid <- expand.grid(.mtry = 2:7)

rfControl <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number = 20, repeats = 5, search="grid", sampling = "rose")

fitRandomForest <- train(as.factor(Survived) ~ . , data.train3, method = "rf", tuneGrid = rfGrid, trControl = rfControl)
## Warning: package 'ROSE' was built under R version 4.0.5
## Loaded ROSE 0.0-4
confusionMatrix(as.factor(predict(fitRandomForest)), as.factor(data.train3$Survived), positive = "TRUE")

The accuracy is only around 82% (recall the individual tree has a training set accuracy of 83-87%), but by blending the effects of many trees one should expect that this overfitting has been significantly addressed and that this model will perform well on the test set, the set that actually matters. With that said, the structure of the model greatly obfuscates the underlying factors in the predictions, making interpretation highly challenging.

Model Selection

Comparing fitRandomForest vs. fitXGBoost

# compare performance of random forest and xgboost models
resamps <- resamples(list(RF = fitRandomForest, XGBoost = fitXGBoost))
bwplot(resamps, metric = "Accuracy")

xyplot(resamps)

Since we used the same sampling approach to train both the random forest and the xgboost model, we can compare them based on their sets of resamples.

The boxplots look pretty similar: one should expect around an 80% accuracy with each of the models.

Additionally, the scatterplot shows fairly strong correlation, suggesting only minimal possible improvement by implementing an ensemble model.

With that said, fitXGBoost has a few extreme resamples. Let’s see if we can somehow ascertain some of the latent signal in the model while maintaining the stability of fitRandomForest.

Considering an Ensemble

xgb <- as.logical(predict(fitXGBoost, data.test3))
rf <- as.logical(predict(fitRandomForest, data.test3))
table(xgb, rf)
##        rf
## xgb     FALSE TRUE
##   FALSE   257   68
##   TRUE      0   93

The boosted trees model seems to under-predict a TRUE outcome for the target (there were 0 occurences in which fitXGBoost predicted TRUE and fitRandomForest predicted FALSE). With that said, maybe we should create an ensemble that predicts whatever the models predict whenever they agree, but when fitXGBoost says FALSE and fitRandomForest says TRUE, we add in some randomness to convert a few extra FALSE’s over to TRUE’s.

fitEnsemble <- as.data.frame(cbind(xgb, rf))
fitEnsemble$comparison <- fitEnsemble$xgb + fitEnsemble$rf

for (i in 1:nrow(data.test3)) {
  set.seed(as.integer(runif(1) * 100))
  if (fitEnsemble$comparison[i] == 1) {
    fitEnsemble$prediction[i] <- runif(1,0,1) > 0.68
  }
  else {
    fitEnsemble$prediction[i] <- as.logical(fitEnsemble$comparison[i])
  }
}
table(fitEnsemble$prediction, rf)
##        rf
##         FALSE TRUE
##   FALSE   257   54
##   TRUE      0  107
# write the predictions to a .csv file
Survived <- as.numeric(fitEnsemble$prediction)             # fitXGBoost.predictions, fitRandomForest.predictions, fitEnsemble$prediction
submittedResults <- data.frame(PassengerId, Survived)
write.csv(submittedResults, "submission.csv", row.names = FALSE)

fitRandomForest, fitXGBoost, and the ensemble, after submitting to Kaggle for assessment on the test set, accurately predicted around 78-80% of the observations, with the random forest model maxing out at 80.1%.

At the time of publication, this accuracy rates in the top 4.54% (2348/51670) of all teams who submitted models for evaluation.

Further hyperparameter tuning, feature generation, alternative models (MARS, GAMs, SVC, NN, etc.), and ensembling would likely improve the model slightly. Perhaps some of these approaches will be attempted in the future.
